   manner designed to identify patterns and relationships which are
   otherwise masked. Applying the method in the context of 'healthy'
   products and using census block group level data, we study consumption
   over several categories in two locations. The analyses show that studies
   involving geographically dispersed data must test for, and take into
   account when required, conceptually sound spatial effects in order to
   accurately assess impact. We also show that while both location and the
   product category have a significant impact on the proportion of healthy
   products purchased, the degree to which consumers choose healthier
   alternatives is a function of the category as well as the location.
